Longevity is often decided by availability of food and water and aggressiveness of predators.

An animal's sole existence is to reproduce. Some animals mature to their reproductive stage quicker than others, and thus, they die quicker than others. To ensure that the best genes are passed on, different animals have developed this different rate. Humans, for example, take a long time to develop to sexual maturity and live long lives because it ensures that only the strongest can survive.

Since animals are really just designed to procreate into the next generation, their length of life probably has something to do with the number of offspring they can produce. Mice and rabbits live very short lives, but they produce lots of offspring, so they don't need to live very long to ensure that their genes live to the next generation. Elephants and Humans generally only have 1 child at a time, so  a much longer life is likely needed to ensure that at least 1 of their offspring survive.

The lifespan of animals depends upon their breeding cycles.  If they can have litters and can breed quickly then they die more quickly as well.  Strictly biologically speaking their purpose is to live and to breed and if they have a short breeding cycle then their life cycle mirrors this.
